{"key":"processedPost-16253432","value":{"id":16253432,"first":16252367,"last":16283603,"when":1337438059,"utime":"05/19/12 05:34 PM","content":"Bacteria on agar is not a 'risk' but an almost certainty.&nbsp; It's better for it to form on the agar where you can transfer the healthy mycelium away than in a grain jar where it's going to ruin the whole thing.<br /><br />If it becomes a real problem, make your agar with nutrients such as malt extract at 1/2 strength.&nbsp; This will actually slow down the bacteria while encouraging any mushroom mycelium to speed up in search of food.&nbsp; When you see mycelium pulling away on its own, transfer it to a new dish and repeat until you have a pure culture.<br />RR","title":"Re: MS to Agar , bacteria risk ?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}